4.name: Pokeball
4.desc: A device for catching wild Pokémon. It's thrown like a ball at a Pokémon, comfortably encapsulating its target.

5.name: Old Rod
5.desc: An old and beat-up fishing rod. Use it by any body of water to fish for wild aquatic Pokémon.

8.name: Full Restore
8.desc: A medicine that can be used to fully restore the HP of a single Pokémon and heal any status conditions it has.

9.name: Leaf Stone
9.desc: A dark green stone containing the fossil of a leaf.

10.name: Fire Stone
10.desc: A bright orange stone that produces a warm glow.

11.name: Water Stone
11.desc: A clear blue stone with small bubbles inside of it.

12.name: Sun Stone
12.desc: A jagged red stone resembling the sun. It's warm to the touch.

13.name: Moon Stone
13.desc: A sharp black stone that sparkles like stars at night.

14.name: Thunder Stone
14.desc: A strange yellow stone that produces a static charge when touched.

15.name: Metal Coat
15.desc: A metallic substance that can be used to cover a Pokémon. Boosts the power of Steel-type moves by 20% when held.

24.name: Ability Capsule
24.desc: A capsule that allows a Pokémon with two Abilities to switch between these Abilities when it is used.

25.name: Ability Urge
25.desc: When used, it activates the Ability of an ally Pokémon.

26.name: Adrenaline Orb
26.desc: Using it makes wild Pokémon more likely to call for help. If held by a Pokémon, it boosts Speed when intimidated. It can be used only once.

27.name: Aloraichium Z
27.desc: Allows Alolan Raichu to upgrade Thunderbolt to a Z-Move, Stoked Sparksurfer.

28.name: Balm Mushroom
28.desc: A rare mushroom which gives off a nice fragrance. A maniac will buy it for a high price.

29.name: Beast Ball
29.desc: A special Pokéball designed to catch Ultra Beasts. It has a low success rate for catching others.

30.name: Big Malasada
30.desc: The Alola region’s local specialty—fried bread. It can be used once to heal all the status conditions of a Pokémon.

31.name: Black Flute
31.desc: A toy flute made from black glass. A maniac will buy it for a high price.

32.name: Blue Flute
32.desc: A toy flute made from blue glass. A maniac will buy it for a high price.

33.name: Bottle Cap
33.desc: A beautiful bottle cap that gives off a silver gleam. Some people are happy to receive one.

35.name: Burn Heal
35.desc: A spray-type medicine for treating burns. It can be used once to heal a Pokémon suffering from a burn.

36.name: Ice Heal
36.desc: A spray-type medicine for freezing. It can be used once to defrost a Pokémon that has been frozen solid.

37.name: Bug Memory
37.desc: A memory disc that contains Bug-type data. It changes the type of the holder if held by a certain species of Pokémon.

38.name: Running Shoes
38.desc: A pair of shoes used to walk faster.

39.name: Rocky Helmet
39.desc: If the holder of this item takes damage, the attacker will also be damaged upon contact.

40.name: Red Card
40.desc: A card with a mysterious power. When the holder is struck by a foe, the attacker is removed from battle.

41.name: Eject Button
41.desc: If the holder is hit by an attack, it will switch with another Pokémon in your party.

42.name: Calcium
42.desc: A nutritious drink for Pokémon. When consumed, it raises the base Sp. Atk stat of a single Pokémon.

43.name: Carbos
43.desc: A nutritious drink for Pokémon. When consumed, it raises the base Speed stat of a single Pokémon.

46.name: HP Up
46.desc: A nutritious drink for Pokémon. When consumed, it raises the base HP of a single Pokémon.

48.name: Iron
48.desc: A nutritious drink for Pokémon. When consumed, it raises the base Defense stat of a single Pokémon.

49.name: Lava Cookie
49.desc: Lavaridge Town’s local specialty. It heals all the status problems of one Pokemon.

50.name: Old Chateau
50.desc: Old Chateau’s hidden specialty. It heals all the status problems of a single Pokémon.

51.name: PP Max
51.desc: It maximally raises the top PP of a selected move that has been learned by the target Pokémon.

52.name: PP Up
52.desc: A medicine that can slightly raise the maximum PP of a single move that has been learned by the target Pokémon.

53.name: Protein
53.desc: A nutritious drink for Pokémon. When consumed, it raises the base Attack stat of a single Pokémon.

54.name: Rare Candy
54.desc: A candy that is packed with energy. It raises the level of a single Pokémon by one.

56.name: Sacred Ash
56.desc: Fully restores the HP of all fainted Pokémon in the party. It can only be used outside of battle. It is consumed after use.

57.name: Bicycle
57.desc: A folding Bike that enables a rider to get around much faster than with Running Shoes.

58.name: Sweet Heart
58.desc: Very sweet chocolate. It restores the HP of one Pokémon by only 20 points.

68.name: Zinc
68.desc: A nutritious drink for Pokémon. When consumed, it raises the base Sp. Def stat of a single Pokémon.

69.name: Bike Voucher
69.desc: The Bike Voucher can be redeemed at the bike shop in Cerulean City for a free Bicycle.

70.name: Santa Hat
70.desc: A fancy red Santa Hat! Merry Christmas!

71.name: Card Key
71.desc: A Card Key for something in Rocket Hideout.

72.name: Red Candycane
72.desc: A Tasty Christmas Treat that Restores 200 HP.

73.name: Green Candycane
73.desc: A Tasty Christmas Treat that Restores 200 HP.

74.name: Rainbow Candycane
74.desc: A Tasty Christmas Treat that Restores 500 HP.

77.name: Gold Teeth
77.desc: This set of golden dentures belongs to the Safari Zone Warden. After finding it in the Safari Zone, the player can exchange it for HM04 (Strength).

78.name: Itemfinder
78.desc: Gift from Professor Oak's aide in the gate of Route 11 if the player has 30 or more Pokémon registered in his or her Pokédex.

79.name: Max Potion
79.desc: Heals a Pokémon to its full HP.

80.name: Lift Key
80.desc: A Key for the lift in Rocket Hideout.

82.name: Pokedex
82.desc: A digital encyclopedia created by Professor Oak as an invaluable tool to Trainers.

83.name: Oak's Parcel
83.desc: When delivered to Professor Oak, he will give the player a Pokédex.

84.name: Silph Scope
84.desc: Silph Co's scope makes unseeable Pokémon visible.

85.name: Secret Key
85.desc: Unlocks the door of Cinnabar Gym.

86.name: Radio
86.desc: The Radio usually allows the players to tune in to the local programs, allowing the player to get tips from Professor Oak and DJ Mary on Prof. Oak's Pokémon Talk, or to let the player tune in to specific channels such as Buena's Password to win prizes.

87.name: S. S.  Ticket
87.desc: Allows admission to the S.S. Anne.

88.name: Town Map
88.desc: Displays a map of the Kanto region.

89.name: Basement Key
89.desc: A Key for the basement in the Goldenrod Mart-

90.name: Clear Bell
90.desc: A very old-fashioned bell that makes a gentle ringing.

92.name: Timer Ball
92.desc: A somewhat different Poké Ball that becomes progressively more effective the more turns that are taken in battle.

93.name: Super Rod
93.desc: An awesome, high-tech fishing rod. Use it at any body of water to fish for wild aquatic Pokémon.

94.name: Plume Fossil
94.desc: A fossil from a prehistoric Pokémon that once lived in the sky. It looks as if it could come from part of its wing.

100.name: Great Ball
100.desc: A good, high-performance Pokéball that provides a higher Pokémon catch rate than a standard Pokéball can.

101.name: Ultra Ball
101.desc: An ultra-high performance Pokéball that provides a higher success rate for catching Pokémon than a Great Ball.

102.name: Master Ball
102.desc: The best Pokéball with the ultimate level of performance. With it, you will catch any wild Pokémon without fail.

107.name: Dragon Scale
107.desc: A very tough and inflexible scale. Dragon-type Pokémon may be holding this item when caught.

108.name: UpGrade
108.desc: A transparent device somehow filled with all sorts of data. It was produced by Silph Co.

109.name: Prism Scale
109.desc: A mysterious scale that causes a certain Pokémon to evolve. It shines in rainbow colors.

110.name: Soothe Bell
110.desc: An item to be held by a Pokémon. The comforting chime of this bell calms the holder, making it friendly.

111.name: GS Ball
111.desc: A nugget of pure gold. Can be sold at a high price.

112.name: Helix Fossil
112.desc: A fossil from a prehistoric Pokémon that once lived in the sea. It might be a piece of a seashell.

113.name: Dome Fossil
113.desc: A fossil from a prehistoric Pokémon that once lived in the sea. It could be a shell or carapace.

114.name: Old Amber
114.desc: A piece of amber that still contains the genetic material of an ancient Pokémon. It's clear with a tawny, reddish tint.

115.name: Root Fossil
115.desc: A fossil from a prehistoric Pokémon that once lived in the sea. It looks as if it could be part of a plant's root.

116.name: Claw Fossil
116.desc: A fossil from a prehistoric Pokémon that once lived in the sea. It appears to be a fragment of a claw.

117.name: Machine Part
117.desc: The Machine Part allows the staff of the Power Plant to resume operations.

120.name: Secret Potion
120.desc: A fantastic medicine dispensed by the pharmacy in Cianwood City. It fully heals a Pokémon of any ailment.

121.name: Heal Powder
121.desc: A very bitter medicine powder. When consumed, it heals all of a Pokémon's status conditions.

122.name: Energy Powder
122.desc: A bitter medicine powder. When consumed, it restores 50 HP to an injured Pokémon.

123.name: Energy Root
123.desc: An extremely bitter medicinal root. When consumed, it restores 200 HP to an injured Pokémon.

124.name: Revival Herb
124.desc: A terribly bitter medicinal herb. It revives a fainted Pokémon and fully restores its maximum HP.

125.name: Fresh Water
125.desc: Water with a high mineral content. When consumed, it restores 30 HP to an injured Pokémon.

126.name: Soda Pop
126.desc: A highly carbonated soda drink. When consumed, it restores 50 HP to an injured Pokémon.

127.name: Lemonade
127.desc: A very sweet and refreshing drink. When consumed, it restores 70 HP to an injured Pokémon.

128.name: Moomoo Milk
128.desc: A bottle of highly nutritious milk. When consumed, it restores 100 HP to an injured Pokémon.

129.name: Berry Juice
129.desc: A 100 percent pure juice made of Berries. When consumed, it restores 20 HP to an injured Pokémon.

130.name: Green tea
130.desc: Tea can be given to the Saffron City guards to be granted access to the city.

131.name: Pass
131.desc: The Pass allows the player to ride the Magnet Train between Saffron City and Goldenrod City.

136.name: Red Scale
136.desc: A scale from the red GYARADOS. It glows red like a flame.

137.name: Silver Wing
137.desc: A strange, silvery feather that sparkles.

138.name: SquirtBottle
138.desc: Allows the player to water a Sudowoodo posing as a tree on Route 36, prompting a battle with the wild Pokémon. After completing the battle, Sudowoodo will no longer block the path to Ecruteak City.

139.name: Meteorite
139.desc: A meteorite that fell from space onto MT. MOON long ago. It is very lumpy and hard.

140.name: Acro Bike
140.desc: A folding bicycle that is capable of stunts like jumps and wheelies.

141.name: Devon Goods
141.desc: A case that contains mechanical parts of some sort made by the Devon Corporation.

142.name: Devon Scope
142.desc: A scope that signals the presence of any unseeable Pokemon. It is made by the Devon Corp.

143.name: Cherish Ball
143.desc: A quite rare Poke Ball that has been specially crafted to commemorate an occasion of some sort.

145.name: Eon Ticket
145.desc: The ticket required for sailing on a ferry to a distant southern island. It features a drawing of an island.

146.name: Go-Googles
146.desc: Nifty goggles to protect eyes from desert sandstorms.

147.name: Letter
147.desc: An extremely important letter to STEVEN from the PRESIDENT of the Devon Corp.

148.name: Mach Bike
148.desc: A folding bicycle that is at least twice as fast as walking.

149.name: Scanner
149.desc: A device used to search for life-forms in water. It looks too difficult to use.

150.name: Storage Key
150.desc: The key to Team Galactic’s sinister warehouse located at the edge of Veilstone City.

154.name: MysticTicket
154.desc: A ticket required to board the ship to Navhel Rock. It glows with a mystic light.

155.name: Escape Rope
155.desc: A long and durable rope. Use it to escape instantly from a cave or a dungeon.

156.name: Powder Jar
156.desc: A jar for storing Berry Powder made using a Berry Crusher.

157.name: Old Sea Map
157.desc: An old map of the sea leading to a Faraway Island.

158.name: Magma Emblem
158.desc: A medal-like item in the same shape as Team Magma's mark.

159.name: Vs. Seeker
159.desc: A device that indicates Trainers who want to battle. Its battery charges while you walk.

160.name: Tri-Pass
160.desc: A pass for ferries between One, Two, and Three Island. It has a drawing of three islands.

161.name: TM Case
161.desc: A case that holds TMs and HMs. It is attached to the Bag’s compartment for important items.

162.name: Azure Flute
162.desc: A flute that puts out echoing sounds that do not seem to be of this world. It is unknown who made it.

163.name: Lunar Wing
163.desc: A feather that glows like the moon. It is said to possess the power to dispel nightmares.

164.name: Member Card
164.desc: A card needed for entering the inn in Canalave City. Oddly, the last date marked on it was 50 years ago.

165.name: Oak's Letter
165.desc: A letter from Prof. Oak. Written in it is a request for you to go to Rt. 224.

166.name: Old Charm
166.desc: An ancient good-luck charm made of Pokémon bones to be taken to the elder of Celestic Town.

168.name: Poké Radar
168.desc: A tool that can search out Pokémon that are hiding in grass. Its battery is recharged as you walk.

169.name: Vs. Recorder
169.desc: An amazing device that can record a battle either between friends or at a special battle facility.

170.name: Tidal Bell
170.desc: A very old-fashioned bell that makes a gentle ringing.

171.name: Dark Stone
171.desc: Zekrom’s body was destroyed and changed into this stone. It is said to be waiting for the emergence of a hero.

172.name: Dowsing Machine
172.desc: Dowsing Machine is a Key Item used to detect hidden items in the vicinity of the user.

173.name: Gracidea
173.desc: A flower sometimes bundled in bouquets to convey gratitude on special occasions like birthdys.

174.name: Light Stone
174.desc: Reshiram’s body was destroyed and changed into this stone. It is said to be waiting for the emergence of a hero.

175.name: Pal Pad
175.desc: A convenient notepad that is used for registering your friends, Friend Codes, and keeping a record of game play.

176.name: Dragon Skull
176.desc: A skull of a Pokémon which was said to have braved the angry waters to fly around the world.

177.name: Liberty Pass
177.desc: A special pass to go to Liberty Garden. Board the ship in Castelia City.

178.name: Lock Capsule
178.desc: A sturdy Capsule that can only be opened with a special key.

179.name: Colress MCHN
179.desc: The Colress Machine forcibly awakens sleeping Pokémon. First used by Colress on Route 4, the player uses this device to awaken a sleeping wild Crustle in Seaside Cave that is blocking the way to where Team Plasma docked the Plasma Frigate after the Opelucid City incident. The awakening Crustle will lash out at the player, forcing them into a battle.

180.name: Magma Stone
180.desc: A very tasty tail of something. It can be sold at a high price to shops.

181.name: Medal Box
181.desc: Attaches roller skates to the bottom of your shoes, allowing you to glide quickly around and perform tricks.

183.name: Oval Charm
183.desc: An oval charm said to increase the chance of Pokémon Eggs being found at the Day Care.

184.name: DNA Splicers
184.desc: A splicer that fuses Kyurem and a certain Pokémon. They are said to have been one in the beginning.

185.name: Elevator Key
185.desc: A card key that activates the elevator in Lysandre Labs. It is emblazoned with Team Flare’s logo.

186.name: Honor Of Kalos
186.desc: A precious symbol that is awarded only to an individual who has done great things for the Kalos region.

187.name: Intriguing Stone
187.desc: A rather curious stone that might appear to be valuable to some. It’s all in the eye of the beholder.

188.name: Revive All Orb
188.desc: A hold item that revives all Pokémon that have fainted.

190.name: Revive
190.desc: A medicine that can revive fainted Pokémon. It also restores half of a fainted Pokémon's HP.

191.name: Silver Disc
191.desc: A disk that can be converted into a Porygon.

192.name: Full Heal
192.desc: A spray-type medicine. It heals all the status problems of a single Pokemon.

194.name: Apricorn Box
194.desc: The Apricorn Box allows the player to pick and store Apricorns.

195.name: Shalour Sable
195.desc: Shalour City’s famous shortbread. It can be used once to heal all the status conditions of a Pokémon.

197.name: Reaper Cloth
197.desc: An eerie cloth imbued with horrifyingly strong spiritual energy. It allows a certain kind of Pokémon to evolve.

198.name: Electirizer
198.desc: A box full of a massive amount of electric energy. It allows a certain kind of Pokémon to evolve.

199.name: Magmarizer
199.desc: A box brimming with a huge amount of magma energy. It allows a certain kind of Pokémon to evolve.

200.name: Shiny Stone
200.desc: An odd stone that shines with dazzling light. It allows certain kinds of Pokémon to evolve.

201.name: TM01 - Mega Punch
201.desc:
[33CCFF]Mega Punch[-]: 
The target is slugged by a punch thrown with muscle-packed power.

202.name: TM02 - Razor Wind
202.desc:
[33CCFF]Razor Wind[-]: 
A two-turn attack. Blades of wind hit opposing Pokémon on the second turn. Critical hits land more easily.

203.name: TM03 - Energy Ball
203.desc:
[33CCFF]Energy Ball[-]: 
The user draws power from nature and fires it at the target. This may also lower the target's Sp. Def stat.

204.name: TM04 - Whirlwind
204.desc:
[33CCFF]Whirlwind[-]: 
The target is blown away, and a different Pokémon is dragged out. In the wild, this ends a battle against a single Pokémon.

205.name: TM05 - Mega Kick
205.desc:
[33CCFF]Mega Kick[-]: 
The target is attacked by a kick launched with muscle-packed power.

206.name: TM06 - Toxic
206.desc:
[33CCFF]Toxic[-]: 
A move that leaves the target badly poisoned. Its poison damage worsens every turn.

207.name: TM07 - Horn Drill
207.desc:
[33CCFF]Horn Drill[-]: 
The user stabs the target with a horn that rotates like a drill. The target faints instantly if this attack hits.

208.name: TM08 - Body Slam
208.desc:
[33CCFF]Body Slam[-]: 
The user drops onto the target with its full body weight. This may also leave the target with paralysis.

209.name: TM09 - Take-Down
209.desc:
[33CCFF]Take-Down[-]: 
A reckless, full-body charge attack for slamming into the target. This also damages the user a little.

210.name: TM10 - Double-Edge
210.desc:
[33CCFF]Double-Edge[-]: 
A reckless, life-risking tackle. This also damages the user quite a lot.

211.name: TM11 - Bubblebeam
211.desc:
[33CCFF]Bubblebeam[-]: 
A spray of bubbles is forcefully ejected at the target. This may also lower its Speed stat.

212.name: TM12 - Water Gun
212.desc:
[33CCFF]Water Gun[-]: 
The target is blasted with a forceful shot of water.

213.name: TM13 - Ice Beam
213.desc:
[33CCFF]Ice Beam[-]: 
The target is struck with an icy-cold beam of energy. This may also leave the target frozen.

214.name: TM14 - Blizzard
214.desc:
[33CCFF]Blizzard[-]: 
A howling blizzard is summoned to strike opposing Pokémon. This may also leave the opposing Pokémon frozen.

215.name: TM15 - Hyper Beam
215.desc:
[33CCFF]Hyper Beam[-]: 
The target is attacked with a powerful beam. The user can't move on the next turn.

216.name: TM16 - Pay Day
216.desc:
[33CCFF]Pay Day[-]: 
Numerous coins are hurled at the target to inflict damage. Money is earned after the battle.

217.name: TM17 - Submission
217.desc:
[33CCFF]Submission[-]: 
The user grabs the target and recklessly dives for the ground. This also damages the user a little.

218.name: TM18 - Counter
218.desc:
[33CCFF]Counter[-]: 
A retaliation move that counters any physical attack, inflicting double the damage taken.

219.name: TM19 - Seismic Toss
219.desc:
[33CCFF]Seismic Toss[-]: 
The target is thrown using the power of gravity. It inflicts damage equal to the user's level.

220.name: TM20 - Rage
220.desc:
[33CCFF]Rage[-]: 
As long as this move is in use, the power of rage raises the Attack stat each time the user is hit in battle.

221.name: TM21 - Mega Drain
221.desc:
[33CCFF]Mega Drain[-]: 
A nutrient-draining attack. The user's HP is restored by half the damage taken by the target.

222.name: TM22 - Solarbeam
222.desc:
[33CCFF]Solarbeam[-]: 
A two-turn attack. The user gathers light, then blasts a bundled beam on the next turn.

223.name: TM23 - Dragon-Rage
223.desc:
[33CCFF]Dragon-Rage[-]: 
This attack hits the target with a shock wave of pure rage. This attack always inflicts 40 HP damage.

224.name: TM24 - Thunderbolt
224.desc:
[33CCFF]Thunderbolt[-]: 
A strong electric blast crashes down on the target. This may also leave the target with paralysis.

225.name: TM25 - Thunder
225.desc:
[33CCFF]Thunder[-]: 
A wicked thunderbolt is dropped on the target to inflict damage. This may also leave the target with paralysis.

226.name: TM26 - Earthquake
226.desc:
[33CCFF]Earthquake[-]: 
The user sets off an earthquake that strikes every Pokémon around it.

227.name: TM27 - Fissure
227.desc:
[33CCFF]Fissure[-]: 
The user opens up a fissure in the ground and drops the target in. The target faints instantly if this attack hits.

228.name: TM28 - Dig
228.desc:
[33CCFF]Dig[-]: 
The user burrows, then attacks on the next turn.

229.name: TM29 - Psychic
229.desc:
[33CCFF]Psychic[-]: 
The target is hit by a strong telekinetic force. This may also lower the target's Sp. Def stat.

230.name: TM30 - Teleport
230.desc:
[33CCFF]Teleport[-]: 
Use it to flee from any wild Pokémon. It can also warp to the last Pokémon Center visited.

231.name: TM31 - Mimic
231.desc:
[33CCFF]Mimic[-]: 
The user copies the target's last move. The move can be used during battle until the Pokémon is switched out.

232.name: TM32 - Double Team
232.desc:
[33CCFF]Double Team[-]: 
By moving rapidly, the user makes illusory copies of itself to raise its evasiveness.

233.name: TM33 - Reflect
233.desc:
[33CCFF]Reflect[-]: 
A wondrous wall of light is put up to reduce damage from physical attacks for five turns.

234.name: TM34 - Bide
234.desc:
[33CCFF]Bide[-]: 
Gives the user a Bide status. A Pokémon that has a Bide status waits, then does double any damage it took under Bide status.

235.name: TM35 - Metronome
235.desc:
[33CCFF]Metronome[-]: 
The user waggles a finger and stimulates its brain into randomly using nearly any move.

236.name: TM36 - Self-Destruct
236.desc:
[33CCFF]Self Destruct[-]: 
The user attacks everything around it by causing an explosion. The user faints upon using this move.

237.name: TM37 - Egg Bomb
237.desc:
[33CCFF]Egg Bomb[-]: 
A large egg is hurled at the target with maximum force to inflict damage.

238.name: TM38 - Fire Blast
238.desc:
[33CCFF]Fire Blast[-]: 
The target is attacked with an intense blast of all-consuming fire. This may also leave the target with a burn.

239.name: TM39 - Swift
239.desc:
[33CCFF]Swift[-]: 
Star-shaped rays are shot at the opposing Pokémon. This attack never misses.

240.name: TM40 - Skull-Bash
240.desc:
[33CCFF]Skull-Bash[-]: 
The user tucks in its head to raise its Defense in the first turn, then rams the target on the next turn.

241.name: TM41 - Softboiled
241.desc:
[33CCFF]Softboiled[-]: 
The user restores its own HP by up to half of its max HP. May also be used in the field to heal HP.

242.name: TM42 - Dream Eater
242.desc:
[33CCFF]Dream Eater[-]: 
The user eats the dreams of a sleeping target. It absorbs half the damage caused to heal its own HP.

243.name: TM43 - Sky Attack
243.desc:
[33CCFF]Sky Attack[-]: 
A second-turn attack move where critical hits land more easily. This may also make the target flinch.

244.name: TM44 - Rest
244.desc:
[33CCFF]Rest[-]: 
The user goes to sleep for two turns. This fully restores the user's HP and heals any status conditions.

245.name: TM45 - Thunder Wave
245.desc:
[33CCFF]Thunder Wave[-]: 
The user launches a weak jolt of electricity that paralyzes the target.

246.name: TM46 - Psywave
246.desc:
[33CCFF]Psywave[-]: 
The target is attacked with an odd psychic wave. The attack varies in intensity.

247.name: TM47 - Explosion
247.desc:
[33CCFF]Explosion[-]: 
The user attacks everything around it by causing a tremendous explosion. The user faints upon using this move.

248.name: TM48 - Rock Slide
248.desc:
[33CCFF]Rock Slide[-]: 
Large boulders are hurled at the opposing Pokémon to inflict damage. This may also make the opposing Pokémon flinch.

249.name: TM49 - Tri-Attack
249.desc:
[33CCFF]Tri-Attack[-]: 
The user strikes with a simultaneous three-beam attack. May also burn, freeze, or leave the target with paralysis.

250.name: TM50 - Substitute
250.desc:
[33CCFF]Substitute[-]: 
The user makes a copy of itself using some of its HP. The copy serves as the user’s decoy.

251.name: TM51 - Endure
251.desc:
[33CCFF]Endure[-]: 
The user endures any attack with at least 1 HP. Its chance of failing rises if it is used in succession.

252.name: TM52 - Dragon Claw
252.desc:
[33CCFF]Dragon Claw[-]: 
The user slashes the target with huge, sharp claws.

253.name: TM53 - Psyshock
253.desc:
[33CCFF]Psyshock[-]: 
The user materializes an odd psychic wave to attack the target. This attack does physical damage.

254.name: TM54 - Calm Mind
254.desc:
[33CCFF]Calm Mind[-]: 
The user quietly focuses its mind and calms its spirit to raise its Sp. Atk and Sp. Def stats.

255.name: TM55 - Roar
255.desc:
[33CCFF]Roar[-]: 
The target is scared off and a different Pokémon is dragged out. In the wild, this ends a battle against a single Pokémon.

256.name: TM56 - Embargo
256.desc:
[33CCFF]Embargo[-]: 
This move prevents the target from using its held item for five turns. Its Trainer is also prevented from using items on it.

257.name: TM57 - Hail
257.desc:
[33CCFF]Hail[-]: 
The user summons a hailstorm lasting five turns. It damages all Pokémon except the Ice type.

258.name: TM58 - Bulk Up
258.desc:
[33CCFF]Bulk Up[-]: 
The user tenses its muscles to bulk up its body, raising both its Attack and Defense stats.
